import numpy as np # linear algebra
import pandas as pd # data processing, CSV file I/O (e.g. pd.read_csv)
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker
from matplotlib.font_manager import FontProperties
import textwrap as twp
import seaborn as sns

# Set modern styling for all plots
plt.style.use('seaborn-v0_8-darkgrid')
sns.set_palette("colorblind")  # Use a colorblind-friendly palette
plt.rcParams['font.family'] = 'sans-serif'
plt.rcParams['font.sans-serif'] = ['Arial', 'DejaVu Sans', 'Liberation Sans']
plt.rcParams['axes.labelsize'] = 12
plt.rcParams['axes.titlesize'] = 14
plt.rcParams['figure.titlesize'] = 16

# Custom color palette for the plots
country_colors = {
    'China': '#1f77b4',
    'India': '#ff7f0e',
    'United States': '#2ca02c',
    'Indonesia': '#d62728',
    'Pakistan': '#9467bd',
    'Brazil': '#8c564b',
    'Nigeria': '#e377c2',
    'Bangladesh': '#7f7f7f',
    'Russia': '#bcbd22',
    'Mexico': '#17becf',
    'Japan': '#aec7e8',
    'Iran': '#ffbb78',
    'Germany': '#98df8a',
    'Canada': '#ff9896',
    'Saudi Arabia': '#c5b0d5',
    'South Korea': '#c49c94'
}

# Load the dataset
df = pd.read_csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/owid/energy-data/master/owid-energy-data.csv")

# Separate countries and regions
countries_list = df[~df['iso_code'].isna() == True ]['country'].unique().tolist()
main_regions_list = ['Asia', 'Africa', 'North America', 'South America', 'Antarctica', 'Europe', 'Australia']

df_regions = df[df['country'].isin(main_regions_list)]
df = df[df['country'].isin(countries_list)]

# Filter years to start from 2000
df = df[df['year']>=2000]

# Find the latest year with complete data for all metrics
required_columns = ['population', 'primary_energy_consumption', 'carbon_intensity_elec', 
                    'electricity_generation', 'greenhouse_gas_emissions']
latest_years = {}

for col in required_columns:
    # Get the years where data exists for this column
    years_with_data = df[df[col].notna()]['year'].unique()
    if len(years_with_data) > 0:
        latest_years[col] = int(max(years_with_data))

# Find the most recent year that has data for all required columns
LATEST_YEAR = min(latest_years.values())
print(f"Latest year with complete data: {LATEST_YEAR}")
print(f"Latest available year per metric: {latest_years}")

# Percentage of total per year calculation
df['population_pct'] = df['population'] / df.groupby('year')['population'].transform('sum')*100
df['primary_energy_consumption_pct'] = df['primary_energy_consumption'] / df.groupby('year')['primary_energy_consumption'].transform('sum')*100
df['electricity_generation_pct'] = df['electricity_generation'] / df.groupby('year')['electricity_generation'].transform('sum')*100
df['greenhouse_emissions_pct'] = df['greenhouse_gas_emissions'] / df.groupby('year')['greenhouse_gas_emissions'].transform('sum')*100

df_regions['population_pct'] = df_regions['population'] / df_regions.groupby('year')['population'].transform('sum')*100
df_regions['primary_energy_consumption_pct'] = df_regions['primary_energy_consumption'] / df_regions.groupby('year')['primary_energy_consumption'].transform('sum')*100
df_regions['electricity_generation_pct'] = df_regions['electricity_generation'] / df_regions.groupby('year')['electricity_generation'].transform('sum')*100

# Create top 10 lists using the latest year with complete data
top_10_population_list = df[df['year']==LATEST_YEAR].nlargest(10, 'population')['country'].to_list()
top_10_electricity_generation_list = df[df['year']==LATEST_YEAR].nlargest(10, 'electricity_generation')['country'].to_list()
top_10_carbon_intensity_list = df[df['year']==LATEST_YEAR].nlargest(10, 'carbon_intensity_elec')['country'].to_list()
bottom_10_carbon_intensity_list = df[df['year']==LATEST_YEAR].nsmallest(10, 'carbon_intensity_elec')['country'].to_list()
top_10_emissions_list = df[df['year']==LATEST_YEAR].nlargest(10, 'greenhouse_gas_emissions')['country'].to_list()

# Create a function for styling tables
def style_table(table, highlight_rows=[0, -1]):
    """Apply consistent styling to tables"""
    table.auto_set_font_size(False)
    table.set_fontsize(10)
    table.scale(1, 2)
    
    # Apply custom coloring
    for (row, col), cell in table.get_celld().items():
        if row in highlight_rows:
            cell.set_text_props(fontproperties=FontProperties(weight='bold'), color='white')
            cell.set_facecolor('#3949ab')
        elif row % 2 == 0:
            cell.set_facecolor('#f5f5f5')
        else:
            cell.set_facecolor('#e1e1e1')
            
        # Add borders
        cell.set_edgecolor('#333333')

# Prepare data for the most carbon intensive countries (electricity)
df_high_carbon = df.query(f'(year in [{LATEST_YEAR}])').nlargest(10, 'carbon_intensity_elec').sort_values(by=['carbon_intensity_elec'], ascending=False)
df_high_carbon.loc['Total',:] = df_high_carbon.sum(axis=0)
df_high_carbon.loc[df_high_carbon.index[-1], 'country'] = 'Average'
df_high_carbon.loc[df_high_carbon.index[-1], 'carbon_intensity_elec'] = df_high_carbon['carbon_intensity_elec'].mean()
df_high_carbon = df_high_carbon.round(2)

# Create figure with enhanced styling
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2, figsize=(15, 12), gridspec_kw={'height_ratios': [3, 1]})
fig.suptitle(f'Carbon Intensity of Electricity Generation in Highest Emission Countries (2000-{LATEST_YEAR})', 
             fontweight='bold', fontsize=18, y=0.98)

# Adding a subtle background color
fig.patch.set_facecolor('#f8f9fa')

# Plot with improved styling
for i, entity in enumerate(top_10_carbon_intensity_list):
    color = country_colors.get(entity, sns.color_palette()[i % 10])
    data = df[df['country']==entity]
    ax1.plot(data['year'], data['carbon_intensity_elec'], 
             label=entity, linewidth=2.5, color=color,
             marker='o', markevery=10, markersize=5)

# Add reference lines and highlights
ax1.axvspan(LATEST_YEAR-12, LATEST_YEAR, color='#f5f5f5', alpha=0.3)

# Add world average for comparison
world_avg_by_year = df.groupby('year')['carbon_intensity_elec'].mean()
ax1.plot(world_avg_by_year.index, world_avg_by_year.values, 
         label='Global Average', linewidth=3, 
         linestyle='--', color='black')

# Improve axis formatting and labels
ax1.set_ylabel('Carbon intensity of electricity (g CO2 equiv. per kWh)', fontweight='bold')
ax1.set_xlabel('Year', fontweight='bold')
ax1.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Add annotations for key trends
# For example, identify a country with notable trend for annotation
try:
    coal_dependent = top_10_carbon_intensity_list[0]
    mid_year = df[df['country']==coal_dependent]['year'].median()
    mid_value = df[(df['country']==coal_dependent) & (df['year']==mid_year)]['carbon_intensity_elec'].values[0]
    
    ax1.annotate('High coal dependency in\nelectricity generation', 
                xy=(mid_year, mid_value),
                xytext=(mid_year-10, mid_value*1.1),
                arrowprops=dict(facecolor='black', shrink=0.05, width=1.5, headwidth=8),
                fontsize=10, fontweight='bold')
except:
    pass

# Enhance legend with better positioning and style
legend = ax1.legend(loc="upper right", frameon=True, fancybox=True, 
                   shadow=True, fontsize=10, title="Countries")
legend.get_title().set_fontweight('bold')

# Create improved table
column_labels = [
    'Country', 
    'Carbon intensity (g CO2e/kWh)', 
    'Fossil share of electricity (%)', 
    'Electricity generation (TWh)'
]

the_table = ax2.table(
    cellText=df_high_carbon[['country','carbon_intensity_elec','fossil_share_elec','electricity_generation']].values, 
    colLabels=column_labels,
    cellLoc='center', 
    loc='center'
)
style_table(the_table)

ax2.axis('off')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.92)

# Improve visual hierarchy
for spine in ax1.spines.values():
    spine.set_linewidth(1.5)
    
# Add a title for the table section
plt.figtext(0.5, 0.48, f'Highest Carbon Intensity Electricity Countries Data for {LATEST_YEAR}', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold', ha='center')

# Add a footnote
plt.figtext(0.5, 0.01, 'Data source: Our World in Data (OWID)', 
           ha='center', fontsize=8, style='italic')

# Get data for latest year
df_latest = df[df['year'] == LATEST_YEAR]

# Filter for countries with significant electricity generation (top 30)
significant_countries = df_latest.nlargest(30, 'electricity_generation')

# Sort by carbon intensity
significant_countries = significant_countries.sort_values('carbon_intensity_elec')

# Create figure
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))

# Create bar chart
#bars = plt.barh(significant_countries['country'], significant_countries['carbon_intensity_elec'])

# Filter out records where carbon_intensity_elec is NaN
filtered_data = significant_countries.dropna(subset=['carbon_intensity_elec'])

# Create bar chart with the filtered data
bars = plt.barh(filtered_data['country'], filtered_data['carbon_intensity_elec'])

# Color bars according to intensity
norm = plt.Normalize(significant_countries['carbon_intensity_elec'].min(), 
                     significant_countries['carbon_intensity_elec'].max())
colors = plt.cm.YlOrRd(norm(significant_countries['carbon_intensity_elec']))

for bar, color in zip(bars, colors):
    bar.set_color(color)

# Add labels and title
plt.xlabel('Carbon intensity of electricity (g CO2 equiv. per kWh)', fontweight='bold')
plt.title(f'Carbon Intensity of Electricity in Major Economies ({LATEST_YEAR})', 
          fontweight='bold', fontsize=16)

# Add grid
plt.grid(axis='x', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Add world average line
world_avg = df_latest['carbon_intensity_elec'].mean()
plt.axvline(x=world_avg, color='black', linestyle='--', linewidth=2)
plt.text(world_avg, -1, f'Global Average: {world_avg:.1f}', 
        ha='center', va='top', fontweight='bold', backgroundcolor='#f8f9fa')

# Adjust layout
plt.tight_layout()

# Add colorbar
fig, ax = plt.gcf(), plt.gca()  # Get current figure and axes
sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap=plt.cm.YlOrRd, norm=norm)
sm.set_array([])
cbar = fig.colorbar(sm, ax=ax)  # Pass the current axes to fix the colorbar issue
cbar.set_label('Carbon Intensity', fontweight='bold')

# Add annotations for notable countries
for i, country in enumerate(significant_countries['country']):
    intensity = significant_countries.iloc[i]['carbon_intensity_elec']
    if country in ['China', 'United States', 'India', 'Russia', 'France', 'Brazil', 'Norway', 'Sweden']:
        plt.text(intensity + 10, i, f'{intensity:.1f}', va='center', fontweight='bold')

# Add a footnote
plt.figtext(0.5, 0.01, 'Data source: Our World in Data (OWID)', 
           ha='center', fontsize=8, style='italic')

# Create scatter plot showing carbon intensity vs electricity generation
# Get data for latest year
df_latest = df[df['year'] == LATEST_YEAR]

# Create figure
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))

# Create scatter plot with size based on total emissions
scatter = plt.scatter(df_latest['electricity_generation'], 
                     df_latest['carbon_intensity_elec'],
                     s=df_latest['greenhouse_gas_emissions']/5,  # Size based on emissions
                     alpha=0.7,
                     c=df_latest['fossil_share_elec'],  # Color based on fossil fuel share
                     cmap='YlOrRd')

# Add labels for key countries
countries_to_label = []
# Top 15 electricity generators
countries_to_label.extend(df_latest.nlargest(15, 'electricity_generation')['country'].tolist())
# Top 5 highest carbon intensity
countries_to_label.extend(df_latest.nlargest(5, 'carbon_intensity_elec')['country'].tolist())
# Top 5 lowest carbon intensity
countries_to_label.extend(df_latest.nsmallest(5, 'carbon_intensity_elec')['country'].tolist())

# Remove duplicates
countries_to_label = list(set(countries_to_label))

for country in countries_to_label:
    country_data = df_latest[df_latest['country'] == country]
    if not country_data.empty:
        x = country_data['electricity_generation'].values[0]
        y = country_data['carbon_intensity_elec'].values[0]
        plt.annotate(country, (x, y), fontsize=9, fontweight='bold',
                    xytext=(5, 5), textcoords='offset points')

# Add labels and title
plt.xlabel('Electricity Generation (TWh)', fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel('Carbon intensity of electricity (g CO2 equiv. per kWh)', fontweight='bold')
plt.title(f'Carbon Intensity vs Electricity Generation ({LATEST_YEAR})', 
          fontweight='bold', fontsize=16)

# Add grid
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Use log scale for x-axis due to wide range
plt.xscale('log')

# Add reference lines
world_avg_intensity = df_latest['carbon_intensity_elec'].mean()
plt.axhline(y=world_avg_intensity, color='black', linestyle='--', linewidth=1.5)
plt.text(plt.xlim()[0]*1.1, world_avg_intensity, f'Global Average: {world_avg_intensity:.1f}', 
        va='center', fontweight='bold', backgroundcolor='#f8f9fa')

# Add colorbar
fig, ax = plt.gcf(), plt.gca()  # Get current figure and axes
sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap='YlOrRd', norm=norm)
sm.set_array([])
cbar = fig.colorbar(sm, ax=ax)  # Pass the current axes to fix the colorbar issue
cbar.set_label('Fossil Fuel Share of Electricity (%)', fontweight='bold')

# Add size legend
sizes = [100, 500, 1000]  # GHG emissions in million tonnes CO2e
for size in sizes:
    plt.scatter([], [], s=size/5, c='gray', alpha=0.5, label=f'{size} Mt CO2e')

plt.legend(title='GHG Emissions', loc='upper right', frameon=True, 
          fancybox=True, shadow=True)

# Add explanatory annotations
plt.annotate('Clean Electricity\n+ Large Generation', 
            xy=(df_latest['electricity_generation'].max()*0.3, world_avg_intensity*0.3),
            xytext=(df_latest['electricity_generation'].max()*0.3, world_avg_intensity*0.3),
            fontsize=12, fontweight='bold', color='green', ha='center')

plt.annotate('Carbon-Intensive Electricity\n+ Large Generation', 
            xy=(df_latest['electricity_generation'].max()*0.3, world_avg_intensity*1.7),
            xytext=(df_latest['electricity_generation'].max()*0.3, world_avg_intensity*1.7),
            fontsize=12, fontweight='bold', color='darkred', ha='center')

# Add a footnote
plt.figtext(0.5, 0.01, 'Data source: Our World in Data (OWID)', 
           ha='center', fontsize=8, style='italic')

# Create a scatter plot to explore the relationship between fossil fuel share and carbon intensity
# Get data for latest year
df_latest = df[df['year'] == LATEST_YEAR].dropna(subset=['carbon_intensity_elec', 'fossil_share_elec'])

# Create figure
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))

# Create scatter plot 
scatter = plt.scatter(df_latest['fossil_share_elec'], 
                     df_latest['carbon_intensity_elec'],
                     s=df_latest['electricity_generation']/5,  # Size based on electricity generation
                     alpha=0.7,
                     c=df_latest['coal_share_elec'],  # Color based on coal share
                     cmap='YlOrRd')

# Add labels for key countries
countries_to_label = []
# Top 15 electricity generators
countries_to_label.extend(df_latest.nlargest(15, 'electricity_generation')['country'].tolist())
# Top 5 highest carbon intensity
countries_to_label.extend(df_latest.nlargest(5, 'carbon_intensity_elec')['country'].tolist())
# Top 5 lowest carbon intensity
countries_to_label.extend(df_latest.nsmallest(5, 'carbon_intensity_elec')['country'].tolist())
# Countries with interesting profiles
countries_to_label.extend(['Norway', 'Sweden', 'France', 'Iceland', 'Qatar', 'Kuwait', 'Saudi Arabia'])

# Remove duplicates
countries_to_label = list(set(countries_to_label))

for country in countries_to_label:
    country_data = df_latest[df_latest['country'] == country]
    if not country_data.empty:
        x = country_data['fossil_share_elec'].values[0]
        y = country_data['carbon_intensity_elec'].values[0]
        plt.annotate(country, (x, y), fontsize=9, fontweight='bold',
                    xytext=(5, 5), textcoords='offset points')

# Add labels and title
plt.xlabel('Fossil Fuel Share of Electricity (%)', fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel('Carbon intensity of electricity (g CO2 equiv. per kWh)', fontweight='bold')
plt.title(f'Relationship Between Fossil Fuel Share and Carbon Intensity ({LATEST_YEAR})', 
          fontweight='bold', fontsize=16)

# Add grid
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Add trend line
z = np.polyfit(df_latest['fossil_share_elec'], df_latest['carbon_intensity_elec'], 1)
p = np.poly1d(z)
plt.plot(np.linspace(0, 100, 100), p(np.linspace(0, 100, 100)), "r--", alpha=0.8)

# Add colorbar
cbar = plt.colorbar(scatter)
cbar.set_label('Coal Share of Electricity (%)', fontweight='bold')

# Add size legend
sizes = [500, 2000, 5000]  # Electricity generation in TWh
for size in sizes:
    plt.scatter([], [], s=size/5, c='gray', alpha=0.5, label=f'{size} TWh')

plt.legend(title='Electricity Generation', loc='upper left', frameon=True, 
          fancybox=True, shadow=True)

# Add annotations to explain interesting patterns
plt.annotate('High gas,\nlow coal mix', 
            xy=(70, 350),
            xytext=(50, 250),
            arrowprops=dict(facecolor='black', shrink=0.05, width=1, headwidth=5),
            fontsize=10, fontweight='bold')

plt.annotate('High coal\ndependency', 
            xy=(90, 850),
            xytext=(70, 950),
            arrowprops=dict(facecolor='black', shrink=0.05, width=1, headwidth=5),
            fontsize=10, fontweight='bold')

# Add a footnote
plt.figtext(0.5, 0.01, 'Data source: Our World in Data (OWID)', 
           ha='center', fontsize=8, style='italic')

# Create a visualization showing carbon intensity trends for major world regions
# Create figure
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))

# Plot trends for each region
for region in main_regions_list:
    data = df_regions[df_regions['country'] == region]
    if not data.empty and data['carbon_intensity_elec'].notna().any():
        plt.plot(data['year'], data['carbon_intensity_elec'], 
                label=region, linewidth=3, 
                marker='o', markevery=10, markersize=6)

# Add global average
global_avg = df.groupby('year')['carbon_intensity_elec'].mean()
plt.plot(global_avg.index, global_avg.values, 
         label='Global Average', linewidth=4, 
         linestyle='--', color='black')

# Add labels and title
plt.xlabel('Year', fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel('Carbon intensity of electricity (g CO2 equiv. per kWh)', fontweight='bold')
plt.title('Carbon Intensity Trends by Region (2000-Latest)', 
          fontweight='bold', fontsize=16)

# Add grid
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Enhance legend
plt.legend(loc="upper right", frameon=True, fancybox=True, 
          shadow=True, fontsize=12)

# Add background color for different eras
plt.axvspan(2000, 2008, color='#fffde6', alpha=0.3, label='Pre-Financial Crisis')
plt.axvspan(2008, 2015, color='#e6ffe6', alpha=0.3, label='Pre-Paris Agreement')
plt.axvspan(2015, LATEST_YEAR, color='#e6ffff', alpha=0.3, label='Post-Paris Agreement')

# Add explanation for trends
important_events = [
    (2008, 'Financial Crisis'),
    (2015, 'Paris Agreement'),
    (2020, 'COVID-19 Pandemic')
]

# Create a visualization showing the relationship between energy mix and carbon intensity
# Get data for latest year for major economies
df_latest = df[df['year'] == LATEST_YEAR].nlargest(20, 'electricity_generation')

# Create figure
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(14, 10))

# Set up the bar width and positions
countries = df_latest['country'].tolist()
x = np.arange(len(countries))
width = 0.15  # Width of the bars

# Sort by carbon intensity
df_latest = df_latest.sort_values('carbon_intensity_elec')
countries = df_latest['country'].tolist()

# Plot the stacked bars for different energy sources
coal_bars = ax.bar(x, df_latest['coal_share_elec'], width, label='Coal', color='#8c564b')
gas_bars = ax.bar(x, df_latest['gas_share_elec'], width, bottom=df_latest['coal_share_elec'], label='Gas', color='#1f77b4')
oil_bars = ax.bar(x, df_latest['oil_share_elec'], width, 
                 bottom=df_latest['coal_share_elec'] + df_latest['gas_share_elec'], 
                 label='Oil', color='#d62728')

# Calculate the remaining share for low-carbon sources
low_carbon_share = 100 - (df_latest['coal_share_elec'] + df_latest['gas_share_elec'] + df_latest['oil_share_elec'])
low_carbon_bars = ax.bar(x, low_carbon_share, width,
                         bottom=df_latest['coal_share_elec'] + df_latest['gas_share_elec'] + df_latest['oil_share_elec'],
                         label='Low-carbon', color='#2ca02c')

# Create a second y-axis for carbon intensity
ax2 = ax.twinx()
intensity_line = ax2.plot(x, df_latest['carbon_intensity_elec'], 'o-', linewidth=2, color='black', label='Carbon Intensity')

# Set x-axis labels
ax.set_xticks(x)
ax.set_xticklabels(countries, rotation=45, ha='right')

# Set labels and title
ax.set_ylabel('Share of Electricity Generation (%)', fontweight='bold')
ax2.set_ylabel('Carbon Intensity (g CO2e/kWh)', fontweight='bold', color='black')
plt.title(f'Electricity Mix vs Carbon Intensity for Top 20 Generators ({LATEST_YEAR})', 
          fontweight='bold', fontsize=16)

# Add grid
ax.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.3)

# Combine legends
lines1, labels1 = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()
lines2, labels2 = ax2.get_legend_handles_labels()
ax.legend(lines1 + lines2, labels1 + labels2, loc='upper center', bbox_to_anchor=(0.5, -0.15),
          fancybox=True, shadow=True, ncol=5)

# Adjust layout
plt.tight_layout()

# Add annotations for notable countries
for i, country in enumerate(countries):
    if country in ['China', 'United States', 'India', 'France', 'Brazil', 'Canada', 'Norway']:
        intensity = df_latest[df_latest['country'] == country]['carbon_intensity_elec'].values[0]
        ax2.annotate(f"{intensity:.0f}", 
                    xy=(i, intensity),
                    xytext=(0, 10), 
                    textcoords="offset points",
                    ha='center', fontweight='bold')

# Add a footnote
plt.figtext(0.5, 0.01, 'Data source: Our World in Data (OWID)', 
           ha='center', fontsize=8, style='italic')

# Create a scatter plot showing the relationship between renewable energy share and carbon intensity
# Get data for latest year
df_latest = df[df['year'] == LATEST_YEAR].dropna(subset=['carbon_intensity_elec', 'renewables_share_elec'])

# Create figure
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))

# Create scatter plot 
scatter = plt.scatter(df_latest['renewables_share_elec'], 
                     df_latest['carbon_intensity_elec'],
                     s=df_latest['electricity_generation']/5,  # Size based on electricity generation
                     alpha=0.7,
                     c=df_latest['solar_share_elec'] + df_latest['wind_share_elec'],  # Color based on modern renewables
                     cmap='Greens')

# Add labels for key countries
countries_to_label = []
# Top 15 electricity generators
countries_to_label.extend(df_latest.nlargest(15, 'electricity_generation')['country'].tolist())
# Top 5 highest renewable share
countries_to_label.extend(df_latest.nlargest(5, 'renewables_share_elec')['country'].tolist())
# Top 5 lowest carbon intensity
countries_to_label.extend(df_latest.nsmallest(5, 'carbon_intensity_elec')['country'].tolist())

# Remove duplicates
countries_to_label = list(set(countries_to_label))

for country in countries_to_label:
    country_data = df_latest[df_latest['country'] == country]
    if not country_data.empty:
        x = country_data['renewables_share_elec'].values[0]
        y = country_data['carbon_intensity_elec'].values[0]
        plt.annotate(country, (x, y), fontsize=9, fontweight='bold',
                    xytext=(5, 5), textcoords='offset points')

# Add labels and title
plt.xlabel('Renewable Energy Share of Electricity (%)', fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel('Carbon intensity of electricity (g CO2 equiv. per kWh)', fontweight='bold')
plt.title(f'Renewable Energy Share vs Carbon Intensity ({LATEST_YEAR})', 
          fontweight='bold', fontsize=16)

# Add grid
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Add trend line
z = np.polyfit(df_latest['renewables_share_elec'], df_latest['carbon_intensity_elec'], 1)
p = np.poly1d(z)
plt.plot(np.linspace(0, 100, 100), p(np.linspace(0, 100, 100)), "r--", alpha=0.8)
correlation = np.corrcoef(df_latest['renewables_share_elec'], df_latest['carbon_intensity_elec'])[0, 1]
plt.text(50, 600, f"Correlation: {correlation:.2f}", fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')

# Add colorbar
fig, ax = plt.gcf(), plt.gca()  # Get current figure and axes
sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap='Greens', norm=norm)
sm.set_array([])
cbar = fig.colorbar(sm, ax=ax)  # Pass the current axes to fix the colorbar issue
cbar.set_label('Solar + Wind Share (%)', fontweight='bold')

# Add size legend
sizes = [500, 2000, 5000]  # Electricity generation in TWh
for size in sizes:
    plt.scatter([], [], s=size/5, c='gray', alpha=0.5, label=f'{size} TWh')
